CDM Reference: Person Occupation.Name Text. The text of the quoted name for the Person Occupation.

The name of the departmental post, nominated by the primary applicant, for any face to face contact with departmental officials. This attribute has been created as an interim measure for SFP1 because ICSE stores the name of the post as nominated by the applicant and does not convert it to a post number. In the future, Contact Post Number should be used in preference to Contact Post Name, and eventually Contact Post Name should be deleted from the CDM.

An Eligibility Test Item is an approval criterion to be satisfied for Visa Subclass. Each Visa subclass has specific eligibility criteria, as defined in the appropriate Regulations. This may support other non-Regulation criteria pertinent to making the final decision. e.g. declarations, agreeing to visa conditions. See issue #18 Visa Issues Register.
A unique identifier for the eligibility test item.
CDM Reference: Eligibility Test Item.Response Text. The text of the response to the eligibility test item on the person visa application. Supporting note provided by client.
CDM Reference: Eligibility Test Item.Response Type. The type of response by the person visa to the test item.
CDM Reference: Eligibility Test Item.Item Type. The name of the type of eligibility item that is being tested on the person visa application.
A Visa Evidence is the physical proof of the grant of a visa. This is normally a visa label attached to a travel document, but also may take other forms such as a wet stamp.

CDM reference: Business Context Identifier.Business Context Id where Business Context Identifier.System Id = EVisa System Id. This is the Transaction Receipt Number used to identify Visa Applications lodged online.
The number of the departmental form which provides the template for the Visa Application.
The user identification, position number, review body or minister who granted the visa. The type of code stored is determined by the GRANTED BY TYPE CODE.
The date that the grant of the visa was made.

The initial date until which a visa (granted onshore), if it continues to be in effect, gives the visa holder a lawful status in Australia. A visa will cease at the end of this day if the visa holder is still in the country. This only applies to visas granted onshore.
The code for the type of location at which the Visa Application is lodged.
The code for the method of lodgement for the Visa Application.
This is the date by which a migrant must make an initial entry. This date is a visa condition for migrant visas. This is also called Initial Entry By Date.
The code for the type of the permission bestowed by the VISA GRANT.

The code for the number of entries into Australia allowed for a visa holder.

The last date on which the visa holder is allowed to enter Australia. The visa will cease if the visa holder is not in the country on or before this date. This is also called Must Not Arrive After date.

CDM Reference: Visa.Grant Number. The GRANT NUMBER uniquely identifies the visa granted to a visa holder. Previously known as VISA GRANT NUMBER. The GRANT NUMBER is a compound data item composed of GRANT POST NUMBER, MACHINE NUMBER and GRANT SERIAL NUMBER.
This is the date which this visa will be in effect until, or was in effect until.

The period for which the visa applicant is permitted to stay in Australia following their initial entry. It takes either: a period expressed in months, years or the letter I (for indefinite)
The number of days, weeks, months or years that a visa holder may stay in Australia. This is used with the VISA STAY PERIOD CODE to calculate the VISA IN EFFECT UNTIL DATE upon arrival.
